Vantage Drilling - The Jackup Emerald Driller Spuds First Wildcat For Ophir In Thailand - Vantage Drilling Co. (OTCMKTS:VTGDF) | Seeking AlphaSign in / Join NowGO»Vantage Drilling - The Jackup Emerald Driller Spuds First Wildcat For Ophir In ThailandOct.22.15 | About: Vantage Drilling (VTGDF) Fun Trading Special situations, contrarian, long/short equity, valueSummaryThe jackup Emerald Driller spudded its first well in Thailand for UK Ophir. A potential eight-well option could be exercised until March 2016, depending on the results.The Emerald Driller secured a two-well extension at a reduced day rate of $80k/d until January 2016, or a 50-day contract.We are still waiting for official news regarding what the company intends to do. A restructuring seems unavoidable at the moment; the question is: What will it be?This article is an update of my preceding article on Vantage Drilling (OTCPK:VTGDF), published on Sept. 30, 2015.

Image: Jackup Emerald Driller, taken from Vantage's website.
On Oct. 21, 2015, we learned the following from Upstreamonline.com:

The independent spun the bit on the Soy Siam prospect probe on Block G4/50 in the western part of the Gulf with the jack-up Emerald Driller.
The G4/50-10 well is targeting Tertiary Miocene sandstones that are equivalent in age to Ophir's producing Bualuang oilfield just 15 kilometres to the north.
Soy Siam has estimated mean prospective resources of 25 million barrels of oil, with a 21% chance of success...
...Once the first probe is drilled, the Vantage Drilling-owned rig will move onto the Parichat South West prospect, where there is a cluster of four fault blocks.
'Each fault block has multiple stacked, Miocene and Oligocene reservoir targets,' Ophir said. The southwest fault block is the initial target, with mean prospective resources again of 25 million barrels of oil, but with a 32% chance of success.
If that well is successful, Ophir said the Parichat South East prospect 'would form an immediate follow-on location.'
'There is considerable additional potential in the event of success in either of these wells,' the company said.



Source: Personal composite.
The estimated cost of the two firm wells is around $18 million, with drilling expected to take a combined 50 days. Initially, the JU Emerald Driller was contracted initially by Ophir until September 2015 at a dayrate of $156k/d. However, after renegotiating -- blend and extend type -- Vantage Drilling was able to push the contract for two-well until early January 2016, and also secure an option for eight-well at a new dayrate of $80k/d applied retroactively from June 2015. Depending on the new results, the company will probably be able to secure a two- or three-month extension at $80k/d.
